data.feb5caf8-3c8b-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b:
AFRH proposed the demolition of the existing Scott Building (Building 80, Non-Contributing) and the construction of a new building on the same site. The new building would be part of the agency’s efforts to consolidate its function on the north end of the campus and to modernize its facilities to reflect current senior living standards and philosophies. The proposed new building will house commons facilities (including dining) and the wellness center, as well as residential units for long-term care and memory support residents. Assisted living residents currently housed in the Scott Building will move to vacant space in the Sheridan Building or will be relocated back to the Gulfport, Mississippi, campus. 


The proposed new building will be three stories in height above the grade of the quadrangle to the north (as viewed from the Sherman Building) and will have an additional below-grade level that will become above grade as the topography of the site slopes to the south.  The massing of the proposed building will be configured to enhance the historic axial relationship among the new building and the Grant, Sherman, and Forwood buildings. The façade of the new building will be formal in massing and style and will create a hard edge to the south side of the quadrangle. The massing of the south side of the buildings will be less formal and will be formed by terraces that step down as the site meets the meadow to the south. This massing scheme allows the building to transition from the formality of the quadrangle to the north to the more picturesque character of the meadow and the residential-scale buildings to the south and southwest. The proposed new building will be oriented to the north and will

have a central entrance that will be generally aligned with the north-south axis created by the Grant, Sherman, and Forwood buildings.

The architectural vocabulary and the articulation of the façade of the proposed new building will be compatible with the historic context of the campus and the surrounding

buildings. Further design review will dictate the void-to-solid ratio, materials, and architectural detailing. 

The proposed new building will have a substantially smaller footprint than the existing Scott Building and will not encroach on the southward view shed from the Lincoln

Cottage (listed as Contributing in the AFRH-W RI/CRM Database and included in the NHL). This view shed, which is identified in the HPP as part of the collective View Shed resource, was compromised by the construction of the Scott Building in the 1950s. As such, the demolition of the Scott Building and the construction of a new, smaller building will restore the historic view shed in its entirety. This condition will be confirmed and documented in the AFRH-W RI/CRM Database once the project is completed. The View Sheds resource will remain a contributing resource to the AFRH-W Historic District, as it is currently listed in the National Register of Historic Places nomination form. Its RLS of “Significant” will not change. 


The demolition of the Scott Building will result in the removal of two existing landscape resources: the Scott Building Grounds and the Scott Building Foundation Plantings. Both of these existing resources are listed as non-contributing in the AFRH-W RI/CRM Database, and the removal of these resources poses no adverse effects. Like the proposed massing of the new building, the new landscaping design will transition from the formality of the quadrangle to the more pastoral setting of the meadow. A landscape plan will be further developed along with the design of the building. There is currently no proposal for alterations to the existing Scott-Sherman Connection (non-contributing) or to the alignment of Scott Drive (non-contributing). 


The Sundial (contributing) located on the Scott Building Grounds will be relocated. The sundial is currently not in its original location, and moving it to another location does not pose any potential adverse effect to the resource or the AFRH-W Historic District.

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 12px;">A soffit board on the side (north) section of the porch of
Quarters 2, evidencing severe rot, was recently damaged by impact by a tree
branch.  Because of the existing rot in
the soffit board, the impact resulted in a large hole.  The hole needs to be repaired immediately to
prevent small animals and debris from entering the exposed area under the porch
roof.  <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p style="font-size: medium;"> </o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 12px;">AFRH-W proposes a temporary repair of the damage to the
porch soffit.  The CRM Manager will then
assist AFRH-W in developing a more permanent and comprehensive solution for
removing the rotten soffit boards and providing ventilation under the porch
eaves. The CR Manager has identified that the damaged soffit board is
non-original plywood, approximately ¼- or ⅛-inch in thickness (see attached
photos).  Before a permanent solution is
developed, the CR Manager will conduct further study to determine whether all
soffit boards on the building’s porch have been replaced with the same plywood
material.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p style="font-size: medium;"> </o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 12px;">The temporary repair will require the removal of the 12-foot
damaged soffit board and replacement with two pieces of Number 1 plywood (one
8-foot span and one 4-foot span) either ¼- or ⅛-inch to match the thickness of
adjacent boards.  The plywood will be
painted to match the surrounding soffit boards and trim. </span><o:p></o:p></p>

data.6da8cd51-3c8a-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b: Masonry Wall and Iron Fence Repair

data.5a8422b0-3cac-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b:
In October 2008, a drunk driver drove a car into the Iron and Masonry Fence on the northwest perimeter of the campus, destroying a single brick pier and causing substantial damage to the stone retaining wall and the iron pickets. The Iron and Masonry Fence was identified as having a relative level of significance of “Significant” in the AFRH-W Resource Inventory. Therefore, repair of this resource requires approval from DCSHPO.


AFRH is proceeding with repairs to the fence and is following the steps required in SOP #4 – Repair, as outlined in Chapter 6 of the AFRH W HPP (2007). AFRH has retained P and P General Contractors, Inc., to perform the work. The contractor’s scope of work includes:

• Reclaim all existing brick, stone, slate, column mouldings, and iron components impacted by the accident.

• Carefully remove mortar from the brick, stone, slate, and mouldings.

• Move the iron fence to an off-site shop where the metal will be carefully straightened using a heat torch.

• Replace any broken or deteriorated anchors from the iron fence by welding on new anchors of equal size and shape. The new anchors will be located in the sample position as the original anchors.

• Paint the iron components to match the existing (black) and re-install the iron components on site.

• Re-install the chain link fence, fence posts, barbed wire, and barbed wire “V” frame supports that were previously attached to the top of the fence.

• Rebuild the brick pier and paint masonry to match the existing (white).

• Rebuild the stone retaining wall and re-install the slate caps.


Mortar samples from the stone wall and brick piers have been sent to Virginia Lime Works (Madison Heights, Virginia) for analysis. Virginia Lime Works will supply an appropriate mortar mix based on their analysis of the composition of the existing mortar samples. New mortar joints will match the adjacent in profile.

data.6da8cd51-3c8a-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b: Golf Hole Relocation and Ball Field Restoration

data.5a8422b0-3cac-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b:
The current design proposal for the golf hole relocation is consistent with the general location proposed and approved in URR #1 (Figures 1, 4, 5, 6, 7). AFRH will relocate the golf holes to the Meadow, which is located in the Savannah I Character Area (as defined in the AFRH-W Historic Preservation Plan). The Meadow is a Contributing resource to the AFRH-W Historic District for its role as a picturesque open space that affords views across campus. The Meadow includes other Contributing landscape resources (see Figure 3) such as clusters of evergreen trees. The Meadow is bounded on the east by Chapel Woods West, which is also a Contributing landscape resource in the Chapel Woods Character Area. The work associated with the relocation will extend south into the Golf Course, a Non-Contributing site. Although mostly unimproved, the project area includes both Contributing and Non-Contributing built resources (see Figure 2) such as Marshall Drive (Contributing), the Marshall Drive Culvert (Contributing), the Central Channel (Non-Contributing), and the Retaining Wall (Contributing).
The proposed design for the golf hole relocation includes grading, removal and replacement of select trees and plantings, and the addition of golf hole features including sand bunkers, greens, paths, and a golf cart ramp (Figure 16). Overall, the proposed use and design retains the open space and significant character of the Meadow and avoids or minimizes adverse effects to historic resources.
The plan remains consistent with the mitigation action defined in 2008 for the 1-to-1 replacement of all removed trees. The existing topography is not historic and has changed since the 1940s; the grading for the golf hole relocation will change the topography, but the grading plan maintains the general topography that characterizes Savannah I. The design also maintains the Meadow's contribution as open space within the historic Spatial Organization of the campus, and views across the meadow will be preserved. Although the Meadow does not include Archeological Sensitivity Zones, as defined in the AFRH-W Historic Preservation Plan (2008), the grading plan avoids impacts to potential remnants of a brick path system that is observed on historic maps of the campus; sections of the brick path system have been uncovered, but the extent and condition of the remnants that are potentially located below grade is unknown.
Ball Field Restoration.
AFRH proposes to restore the softball field that was previously located in the northeast corner of the Meadow. The Ball Field is identified as a Non-Contributing resource to the AFRH-W Historic District and dates sometime after the construction of the Scott Building in the early 1950s. Although not historic, the Ball Field is important to the operations of AFRH-W because of its accommodation of recreational activities that are enjoyed by both residents and staff. AFRH temporarily removed the Ball Field to provide a staging area for the construction of the New Scott Building between 2011 and 2013. AFRH is eager to replace the Ball Field and restore softball as a part of resident life on campus. AFRH proposes to place the Ball Field in the same location in the northeast corner of the Meadow and to make minor improvements to its features. The proposed design meets the challenge of combined use of the Meadow for softball and golf by creating dual purposes for some features.

data.5a8422b0-3cac-11ea-b9b7-027f24e6fd6b:
An exterior copper downspout on the rear (west) elevation of Quarters 1 is clogged by a fallen leaf screen, preventing proper drainage of rainwater. Overflow of the downspout during heavy storms has caused water to enter the interior of the building under the roof, resulting in interior damage to the plaster walls of an upstairs bedroom and bathroom. Quarters 1, as part of the United States Airmen’s and Soldiers’ Home National Historic Landmark, has a relative level of significance of “Key” in the AFRH-W Resource Inventory. Therefore, repairs to take place on both the interior and exterior of this resource require approval from DCSHPO. AFRH is proceeding with repairs to address both the clog in the downspout and the damage that has occurred to the interior plaster surfaces.


EXTERIOR: Several attempts have been made to unclog the downspout. However, the cause of the clog has been identified as a fallen leaf screen, which cannot be dislodged from either end of the downspout. Therefore, the contractor must cut into the copper downspout to remove the leaf screen. The location of the leaf screen has been identified; therefore, the size and visibility of the incision in the copper downspout can be minimized. After the clog has been addressed, the downspout will be soldered to properly seal the incision. A new leaf screen will be installed to prevent future clogging.


INTERIOR: Damage to the interior plaster walls will be repaired using in-kind patching and/or replacement materials. All work will be consistent with guidance provided in Preservation Brief #21: Restoring Historic Flat Plaster – Walls and Ceilings, published by the National Park Service. Areas of damage to the coved wood crown moulding will be repaired using in-kind replacement moulding that replicates the profile of the original/adjacent. All surfaces will be finished and painted to match adjacent surfaces.
